Analysis summary for ds001_breast

I analyzed 50000 patient records with progression-free survival `pfs_months` as the outcome. Mean PFS was 4.693 months (SD 2.496). Models were ordinary least squares on the natural month scale; primary adjusted models included age, ECOG performance status, stage IV status, brain/liver/bone metastases, receptor and mutation markers, Ki-67, tumor size, albumin, 6-month weight loss, and treatment indicators. Interaction models added the relevant main effects and interaction term.

Baseline clinical effects were strong and directionally coherent. Older age was associated with longer PFS (+0.176 months per year, p<1e-250), while worse ECOG performance status (-1.172 months per point, p<1e-250), stage IV disease (-1.549 months, p<1e-250), and brain metastases (-0.983 months, p<1e-250) were associated with shorter PFS. Liver and bone metastasis main effects were not independently prominent after adjustment in the exploratory model.

Tumor biology showed a clear hormone-receptor and proliferation pattern. ER positivity was independently favorable (+0.532 months, p<1e-250), whereas HER2 positivity (-0.471 months, p<1e-250), PIK3CA mutation (-0.582 months, p<1e-250), higher Ki-67 (-0.0189 months per percentage point, p<1e-250), lower albumin, and greater recent weight loss were associated with shorter PFS. PR positivity did not retain an independent main effect after ER and other markers were included.

Treatment main effects were dominated by palbociclib. Adjusted palbociclib exposure was associated with +1.102 months PFS (p<1e-250). Tamoxifen, trastuzumab, olaparib, pembrolizumab, and sacituzumab govitecan did not show comparably strong adjusted main effects in the primary model.

The most important treatment heterogeneity was for palbociclib. Its association was much more favorable in ER-positive patients (+1.559 interaction months, p<1e-250) and PR-positive patients (+1.029 interaction months, p<1e-250), but much less favorable with PIK3CA mutation (-1.665 interaction months, p<1e-250), higher Ki-67 (-0.053 months per Ki-67 point, p<1e-250), and HER2 positivity (-1.338 interaction months, p<1e-250). This implies the strongest apparent palbociclib benefit in hormone-receptor-positive, PIK3CA-wild-type, lower-proliferation disease.

Other treatment-biomarker hypotheses were mostly unsupported. Trastuzumab did not have a meaningful HER2-positive interaction (+0.009 months, p=0.808), olaparib did not have an adjusted any-BRCA-mutation interaction (+0.045 months, p=0.606), and pembrolizumab had only a nonsignificant triple-negative interaction (+0.068 months, p=0.0836). Sacituzumab govitecan showed a small positive interaction in patients with brain metastases (+0.196 months, p=0.00180), which should be interpreted cautiously because it emerged among many exploratory interactions.

Feature-feature interactions suggested molecular subtype structure beyond main effects. The adverse PIK3CA association was stronger in ER-positive disease (-0.826 interaction months, p<1e-250), the adverse Ki-67 slope was stronger in ER-positive disease (-0.026 months per Ki-67 point, p<1e-250), and the PIK3CA adverse association was weaker in HER2-positive disease (+0.720 interaction months, p<1e-250). The positive age association was attenuated in stage IV disease (-0.0106 months per year, p<1e-250).

Overall, 21 of 25 stated hypotheses were statistically significant at p<0.05. The core conclusion is that PFS in this cohort is shaped by disease stage, performance status, brain metastases, nutritional/inflammatory reserve, and breast cancer subtype markers, with a particularly strong palbociclib signal concentrated in ER/PR-positive and PIK3CA-wild-type, lower-Ki-67 subgroups. Several biologically plausible therapy-matching hypotheses for trastuzumab, olaparib, and pembrolizumab were not supported after adjustment in this dataset.

 succeeded in 1290ms:
Dataset ds001_breast contained 50,000 breast oncology patient records with pfs_months as the outcome. I analyzed the Parquet data in place using large-sample linear models for adjusted effects, interaction models for subgroup heterogeneity, and Welch comparisons for treatment effects inside clinically defined subgroups. Effect estimates below are in months of PFS.

The strongest adverse clinical factors were stage IV disease, worse ECOG performance status, and brain metastases. In the multivariable model, `stage_iv` was associated with -1.549 months of PFS, each one-point increase in `ecog_ps` with -1.172 months, and `has_brain_mets` with -0.983 months; all had p < 1e-300. A clinically plausible liver-metastasis effect was not supported after adjustment (`liver_mets` coefficient -0.019 months, p = 0.191). Higher `age_years` was unexpectedly associated with longer PFS (+0.176 months per year, p < 1e-300).

Nutritional and tumor-activity markers were also important. Higher `albumin_g_dl` was favorable (+0.475 months per g/dL, p < 1e-300), while `weight_loss_pct_6mo` (-0.077 months per percentage point, p < 1e-300), `ldh_u_l` (-0.052 months per 100 U/L, p = 2.22e-16), and `ki67_pct` (-0.0189 months per percentage point, p < 1e-300) were adverse.

Biomarker main effects separated into supported and unsupported findings. `er_positive` was independently favorable (+0.532 months, p < 1e-300), whereas `pr_positive` added little after ER and other adjustment (+0.014 months, p = 0.330). `her2_positive` (-0.471 months, p < 1e-300) and `pik3ca_mutation` (-0.582 months, p < 1e-300) were adverse.

The clearest treatment signal was for `treatment_palbociclib`. Its adjusted main association was +1.101 months (p < 1e-300), and interaction analyses showed strong biomarker heterogeneity. The palbociclib association was much larger in hormone-receptor-positive/HER2-negative disease (interaction +1.796 months, p < 1e-300). It was attenuated in `pik3ca_mutation` disease (interaction -1.665 months), with `ki67_pct` >= 20 (interaction -1.445 months), in triple-negative disease (interaction -1.380 months), and in HER2-positive disease (interaction -1.337 months); all of these interaction p-values were < 1e-300. Within triple-negative patients, the palbociclib mean difference was essentially zero (+0.004 months, p = 0.928).

Several clinically plausible targeted-treatment hypotheses were not supported in this cohort. Among ER-positive patients, `treatment_tamoxifen` was associated with only +0.023 months (p = 0.450). Among HER2-positive or HER2-amplified patients, `treatment_trastuzumab` was not favorable (-0.044 months, p = 0.367). Among BRCA1/2-mutated patients, `treatment_olaparib` showed +0.016 months (p = 0.733). In triple-negative patients, `treatment_pembrolizumab` (+0.052 months, p = 0.368) and `treatment_sacituzumab_govitecan` (+0.062 months, p = 0.316) were not significant. A pembrolizumab-by-high-NLR interaction was negative (-0.067 months for `nlr` >= 4) but did not meet the 0.05 threshold (p = 0.062).

Overall, the dataset showed strong prognostic structure around stage, ECOG status, brain metastases, albumin, weight loss, LDH, Ki67, ER status, HER2 positivity, and PIK3CA mutation. Treatment heterogeneity was dominated by palbociclib: benefit was concentrated in HR-positive/HER2-negative disease and was sharply reduced in PIK3CA-mutated, high-Ki67, triple-negative, and HER2-positive subgroups. Other targeted-therapy subgroup hypotheses were not statistically supported by the analyses run here.

 succeeded in 1348ms:
Dataset ds001_breast contains 50,000 breast oncology records with no missing values and one outcome, pfs_months. Mean PFS was 4.693 months (SD 2.496; range 0 to 16.660). I used adjusted OLS models on the natural month scale, then added product terms for targeted subgroup and interaction tests. Very small p-values are reported as 1e-300 when they underflowed the normal approximation used for the large-sample OLS z tests.

The strongest adjusted prognostic patterns were consistent across iterations. Higher age_years was associated with longer PFS (+0.1757 months/year, p<1e-300), while worse ecog_ps (-1.1717 months per point), stage_iv (-1.5487 months), and has_brain_mets (-0.9831 months) were strongly associated with shorter PFS. ER-positive disease had longer PFS (+0.5315 months), whereas HER2-positive disease (-0.4710 months), pik3ca_mutation (-0.5816 months), higher ki67_pct (-0.0189 months per percentage point), lower albumin_g_dl (+0.4757 months per g/dL), higher weight_loss_pct_6mo (-0.0768 months per percentage point), and higher ldh_u_l (-0.0005 months per U/L) all pointed toward worse outcomes.

Treatment main effects were concentrated in palbociclib. treatment_palbociclib was associated with +1.1014 adjusted months of PFS (p<1e-300). treatment_tamoxifen, treatment_trastuzumab, treatment_olaparib, and treatment_pembrolizumab did not show meaningful adjusted main effects. treatment_sacituzumab_govitecan was borderline significant but extremely small (+0.0334 months, p=0.0495), so I would not interpret it as a clinically meaningful main effect.

The main treatment-biomarker finding was palbociclib heterogeneity. The palbociclib association was much larger in er_positive patients (interaction +1.5585 months, p<1e-300); raw palbociclib differences were +1.577 months in ER-positive patients and -0.017 months in ER-negative patients. In contrast, pik3ca_mutation nearly abolished the palbociclib-associated gain (interaction -1.6653 months, p<1e-300); raw differences were +1.659 months in PIK3CA-wildtype patients and +0.036 months in mutated patients. In a simultaneous interaction model, the palbociclib by er_positive interaction remained large (+1.5099 months), the palbociclib by pik3ca_mutation interaction remained strongly negative (-1.6565 months), and pr_positive added only a small additional increment (+0.0575 months, p=0.0296).

PIK3CA also showed biomarker-biomarker heterogeneity: the adverse pik3ca_mutation association was substantially stronger in er_positive patients (interaction -0.8260 months, p<1e-300; -0.8392 months in the simultaneous palbociclib interaction model). This suggests the poor-prognosis PIK3CA signal is concentrated in the ER-positive context in this cohort.

Several clinically plausible treatment-subgroup hypotheses were not supported. The treatment_trastuzumab by her2_positive interaction was null (+0.0219 months, p=0.501), and interactions with her2_amplification and her2_low were also null. Olaparib did not show significant adjusted interaction with brca1_mutation (+0.0774 months, p=0.484) or brca2_mutation (-0.0448 months, p=0.687), despite a small unadjusted BRCA-mutated subgroup difference. Pembrolizumab did not show a significant triple-negative interaction (+0.0326 months, p=0.349), and sacituzumab govitecan did not show a triple-negative interaction (+0.0473 months, p=0.251). Pembrolizumab had a borderline small negative interaction with high nlr (nlr >= 4: -0.0607 months, p=0.0490), which is statistically fragile and much smaller than the palbociclib interactions.

Additional interaction probes did not show meaningful compounding of baseline risk: stage_iv did not interact with has_brain_mets (+0.0074 months, p=0.841), liver_mets (tested separately, p=0.153), or low albumin (-0.0214 months, p=0.410). A small independent brca1_mutation association was detected (-0.0689 months, p=0.0327), but its magnitude was clinically minor.

Overall, the cohort shows a strong prognostic structure dominated by performance status, stage, brain metastases, ER/HER2/PIK3CA biology, proliferation, nutrition/inflammation proxies, and one major treatment-biomarker-treatment interaction: palbociclib benefit appears concentrated in ER-positive and PIK3CA-wildtype disease. Most other treatment-biomarker hypotheses were statistically unsupported after adjustment.

